== History == DBC News was established on 21 September 2016 by Iqbal Sobhan Chowdhury. He is the Media Adviser to Prime Minister of Bangladesh, [[Sheikh Hasina]]. Sahidul Ahsan was the founding managing director while Monjurul Islam was the founding news editor. The opening was attended by [[Ministry of Commerce (Bangladesh)|Commerce Minister]] [[Tofail Ahmed (politician)|Tofail Ahmed]] and [[Ministry of Information (Bangladesh)|Information Minister]] [[Hasanul Haq Inu]].<ref name="thedailystar_1287730"/><ref name=":1" /> It started with the broadcast of the 10 am news.<ref name=":0" />
=== Censorship and violence === On 27 October 2017, a motorcade of former Prime Minister [[Khaleda Zia]] was attacked in [[Feni District]]. The news van of DBC and other news organizations were damaged in the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/politics/2017/10/28/khaledas-motorcade-attacked-feni/|title=Khaleda's motorcade attacked in Feni|date=2017-10-28|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref> DBC News correspondent Partho Hasan was attacked by Shirhan Sharif Tomal, Bangladesh Jubo League leader and son of Land Minister [[Shamsur Rahman Sherif]], on 29 November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/attack-journos-jubo-league-expels-land-ministers-son-1505242|title=Attack on Journos: Jubo League expels land minister's son|date=2017-12-15|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/4-journalists-beaten-pabna-1498459|title=4 journalists beaten up in Pabna|date=2017-11-30|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en}}</ref> Bangladesh Police closed eight members of the [[Detective Branch (Bangladesh)|Detective Branch]] of [[Barisal Metropolitan Police]] for torturing a cameraman of DBC in Barisal on 12 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/nation/2018/03/13/eight-db-police-closed-torture-journalist-barisal/|title=Eight DB police closed over torture of journalist in Barisal|date=2018-03-13|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observerbd.com/bn/details.php?id=10347|title=ডিবিসি নিউজ'র সাংবাদিককে নির্যাতনের প্রতিবাদে মানববন্ধন|last=|first=|date=|website=observerbd.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> The police team that attacked the journalist were led by sub-inspector Abul Bashar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unb.com.bd/bangladesh-news/5-more-cops-suspended-over-Barisal-journo-torture/65900|title=5 more cops suspended over Barisal journo torture|last=News|first=United|work=unb.com.bd|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/nation/2018/03/15/constable-suspended-torture-dbc-news-cameraperson|title=Constable suspended over torture of DBC News cameraperson in Barisal|date=2018-03-14|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref> According to the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] [[Human Rights Report]] for 2017 the government of Bangladesh forced DBC news to remove a news item tiled “Bangladesh’s Hasina Survives another Attempt on Her Life.” The news was sourced to a Burmese news portal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/law-and-rights/2018/04/21/us-significant-limitations-freedom-speech-bangladesh-2017|title=US: Significant limitations on freedom of speech in Bangladesh in 2017|date=2018-04-21|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref>
