{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Indo-Latvian|India|Latvia|map=India Latvia Locator (cropped).png}}

'''India–Latvia relations''' refer to the bilateral relations between [[India]] and [[Latvia]]. Two countries established diplomatic relations at 1991, following the independence of Latvia.<ref>{{cite url|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/Portal/ForeignRelation/Latvia_2015_07_02.pdf|title=India-Latvia relations}}</ref> India's mission to Latvia is accredited from the Indian embassy in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]; while Latvia maintains an embassy and a consulate in [[New Delhi]].

==Economic relations==
In 2013, Latvia and India signed an agreement avoiding double taxation, which increased Indian exports to Latvia in term of economic benefits between two nations.<ref>{{cite url|url=http://irlat.com/latvia-india-double-taxation-avoidance-agreement-to-be-signed-in-near-future/|title=LATVIA-INDIA DOUBLE TAXATION AVOIDANCE AGREEMENT TO BE SIGNED IN NEAR FUTURE|date=7 May 2013}}</ref> Currently two countries are discussing on building a closer and deeper cooperation in transports and logistics.<ref>{{cite url|url=http://www.mfa.gov.lv/en/news/latest-news/56959-latvia-and-india-need-to-build-closer-cooperation-in-transport-and-logistics|title=Latvia and India need to build closer cooperation in transport and logistics}}</ref>

India sees Latvia, as well as [[Estonia]] and [[Lithuania]], as strategic partners of Indian interests in the [[Baltics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lu.lv/eng/news/t/4551/|title=From India to Latvia: Interest in the Baltic States Brings to Riga}}</ref>

==State visits==
In 2017, Latvian Prime Minister [[Māris Kučinskis]] visited India to accelerate the development of economic relations between the countries.<ref>{{cite url|url=https://www.mk.gov.lv/en/aktualitates/kucinskis-objective-visit-india-accelerate-development-economic-relations-between|title=Kučinskis: The objective of visit to India is to accelerate the development of economic relations between the countries|date=3 November 2017}}</ref>

